Sorting Algorithms 
The TreapSort algorithm is designed to specifically work with the Treap structure, giving it an O(n log n) complexity in terms of the average case. In general, this method consists of two parts: 
• Inserting all n elements into the empty treap 
• Performing an in-order tree traversal, which yields sorted elements in O(n) 
Each insertion step takes O(log n) in terms of average case complexity, thus, the whole algorithm takes expected O(n log n) time. 
We can see that inserting elements into a treap preserves both binary search tree ordering (due to keys) and balance of nodes, which is achieved through random assignment of priorities for each element. As a result, even if we provide treap-sort with already sorted data, its structure wouldn’t be changed dramatically. 
